<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter subject="Chemistry" id="124" name="Haloalkanes and Haloarenes">
    <easy>
        <question>
            <text>Replacement of hydrogen atom in an aliphatic hydrocarbon by halogen atom gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Haloalkane (Alkyl halide)</option><option id="B">Haloarene</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Contains sp3 hybridized C-X bond.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Replacement of hydrogen atom in an aromatic hydrocarbon by halogen atom gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Haloarene (Aryl halide)</option><option id="B">Haloalkane</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Contains sp2 hybridized C-X bond.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Compounds containing -CH2X group attached to sp3 carbon are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Primary (1°) alkyl halides</option><option id="B">Secondary (2°)</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Halogen is attached to a primary carbon.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Alkyl halides have higher boiling points than parent hydrocarbons because of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Polar nature and higher molecular mass</option><option id="B">Lower mass</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Stronger dipole-dipole and van der Waals forces.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>As the size of halogen atom increases, the boiling point of alkyl halides ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Increases (RF &lt; RCl &lt; RBr &lt; RI)</option><option id="B">Decreases</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Increase in van der Waals forces with size.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Among isomeric alkyl halides, more the branching, ____ the boiling point.</text>
            <option id="A">Lower</option><option id="B">Higher</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Decreased surface area leads to weaker forces.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Alkyl halides are ____ in water.</text>
            <option id="A">Insoluble (Slightly soluble)</option><option id="B">Highly soluble</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Cannot form hydrogen bonds with water molecules.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Density of alkyl halides ____ with increase in number of halogen atoms.</text>
            <option id="A">Increases</option><option id="B">Decreases</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mass increases significantly.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reaction of alcohols with PCl3 gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Alkyl chloride and Phosphorous acid (H3PO3)</option><option id="B">POCl3</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>3ROH + PCl3 -&gt; 3RCl + H3PO3.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Best method for preparing alkyl chlorides from alcohols uses ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Thionyl chloride (SOCl2)</option><option id="B">HCl</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>By-products SO2 and HCl are escapable gases.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Free radical halogenation of alkanes gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Mixture of mono and polyhaloalkanes</option><option id="B">Pure monohaloalkane</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Difficult to separate, low yield for specific isomer.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Addition of hydrogen halides to alkenes follows ____ rule.</text>
            <option id="A">Markovnikov's</option><option id="B">Saytzeff's</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Negative part adds to carbon with fewer H atoms.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reaction of Br2 with propene in CCl4 yields ____.</text>
            <option id="A">1,2-dibromopropane (Vicinal dihalide)</option><option id="B">1-bromopropane</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Anti addition to double bond.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Finkelstein reaction is used to prepare ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Alkyl iodides (RI)</option><option id="B">Alkyl fluorides</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>R-X + NaI -&gt; R-I + NaX (in dry acetone).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Swarts reaction is used to prepare ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Alkyl fluorides (RF)</option><option id="B">Alkyl iodides</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Uses metallic fluorides like AgF, Hg2F2.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Direct halogenation of benzene requires a catalyst like ____.</text>
            <option id="A">FeCl3 / Anhydrous AlCl3 (Lewis acid)</option><option id="B">Bright light</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Electrophilic substitution.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reaction of aniline with NaNO2 + HCl at 0-5°C gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Benzene diazoniun chloride</option><option id="B">Chlorobenzene</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Diazotization reaction.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Replacement of diazonium group by halide using Cu2X2 is ____ reaction.</text>
            <option id="A">Sandmeyer's</option><option id="B">Gattermann's</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Efficient for Cl and Br.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reaction of diazonium salt with KI gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Iodobenzene</option><option id="B">Benzene</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Doesn't require copper catalyst.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Nucleophilic substitution: SN2 stands for ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Bimolecular Nucleophilic Substitution</option><option id="B">Secondary Substitution</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Rate depends on both haloalkane and nucleophile.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>In SN2 reaction, the geometry of product is ____ with respect to reactant.</text>
            <option id="A">Inverted (Walden Inversion)</option><option id="B">Retained</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Backside attack by nucleophile.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Nucleophilic substitution: SN1 stands for ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Unimolecular Nucleophilic Substitution</option><option id="B">Primary Substitution</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Rate depends only on haloalkane concentration.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>SN1 reaction proceeds through a stable ____ intermediate.</text>
            <option id="A">Carbocation</option><option id="B">Carbanion</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Two-step mechanism.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reactivity order of alkyl halides in SN1 is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">3° &gt; 2° &gt; 1°</option><option id="B">1° &gt; 2° &gt; 3°</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Based on stability of carbocation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reactivity order of alkyl halides in SN2 is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">1° &gt; 2° &gt; 3°</option><option id="B">3° &gt; 2° &gt; 1°</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Based on steric hindrance.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Elimination of HX from haloalkane is called ____ reaction.</text>
            <option id="A">Dehydrohalogenation</option><option id="B">Dehydration</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Usually using alcoholic KOH.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Preferential formation of more substituted alkene in elimination is ____ rule.</text>
            <option id="A">Saytzeff's (Zaitsev's)</option><option id="B">Markovnikov's</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Most stable alkene is major.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Grignard reagents have general formula ____.</text>
            <option id="A">R-Mg-X</option><option id="B">R-Li</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Organometallic compounds.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Wurtz reaction: 2RX + 2Na (dry ether) -&gt; ____.</text>
            <option id="A">R-R (Higher alkane)</option><option id="B">R-H</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Coupling of two alkyl groups.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Haloarenes are ____ reactive than haloalkanes towards nucleophilic substitution.</text>
            <option id="A">Less</option><option id="B">More</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Resonance, sp2 carbon and partial double bond character.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Fitting reaction: Aryl halide + Na + Aryl halide -&gt; ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Biphenyl (Diphenyl)</option><option id="B">Toluene</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Aromatic analog of Wurtz.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Wurtz-Fittig reaction: Aryl halide + Na + Alkyl halide -&gt; ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Alkylbenzene</option><option id="B">Biphenyl</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mixed coupling.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Trichloromethane is commonly called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Chloroform</option><option id="B">Iodoform</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Anaesthetic (historically).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Triiodomethane is commonly called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Iodoform</option><option id="B">Chloroform</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Yellow solid used as antiseptic.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Freons are ____ compounds.</text>
            <option id="A">Chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs)</option><option id="B">Hydrocarbons</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Used in refrigeration, ozone depleting.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>DDT stands for ____.</text>
            <option id="A">p,p'-Dichlorodiphenyltrichloroethane</option><option id="B">Diethyl dichloro toluene</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Powerful insecticide.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Ambidentate nucleophiles have ____ nucleophilic centers.</text>
            <option id="A">Two (e.g. CN-, NO2-)</option><option id="B">One</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Can attack through either end.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Haloalkanes are used as starting materials for many ____ synthesis.</text>
            <option id="A">Organic</option><option id="B">Inorganic</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Highly versatile.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Halogen atom in haloarenes is an ____ director.</text>
            <option id="A">ortho and para</option><option id="B">meta</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to resonance effect (+R).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Halogen atom in haloarenes ____ the ring towards electrophilic substitution.</text>
            <option id="A">Deactivates (slightly)</option><option id="B">Activates</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to -I effect dominating over +R in reactivity.</explanation></question>
    </easy>
    <medium>
        <question>
            <text>KCN reacting with RX gives Cyanide (RCN), but AgCN gives Isocyanide (RNC)? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Yes (KCN is ionic, AgCN is covalent)</option><option id="B">No</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Free CN- ion attacks through C; Ag-C bond restricts attack to N.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>KNO2 reacts with RX to give Nitrite (R-ONO), but AgNO2 gives Nitroalkane (R-NO2)? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>KNO2 is ionic (O- attacks); AgNO2 is covalent (N lone pair attacks).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Polarity of C-X bond: Order of Dipole Moment is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">CH3Cl &gt; CH3F &gt; CH3Br &gt; CH3I</option><option id="B">CH3F &gt; CH3Cl</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Anomalous order (Cl &gt; F) due to F-C bond length being too small.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>In SN2, which is more reactive: 1-chlorobutane or 1-chloro-2-methylpropane?</text>
            <option id="A">1-chlorobutane</option><option id="B">1-chloro-2-methylpropane</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Branching near C-X bond increases steric hindrance.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following is more reactive in SN1: 2-bromo-2-methylpropane or 2-bromobutane?</text>
            <option id="A">2-bromo-2-methylpropane (Tertiary)</option><option id="B">2-bromobutane (Secondary)</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Tertiary carbocation is more stable.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Haloalkanes show optical activity when they have ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Chiral carbon atom</option><option id="B">Symmetry center</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Four different groups attached to carbon.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reaction of Chloroform with air in light produces poisonous gas ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Phosgene (COCl2)</option><option id="B">Mustard gas</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Oxidizes to carbonyl chloride.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>1% Ethanol is added to Chloroform bottles to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Convert phosgene to harmless ethyl carbonate</option><option id="B">Act as stabilizer</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Safety measure.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A racemic mixture is an equimolar mixture of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Dextro (d) and Laevo (l) enantiomers</option><option id="B">Structural isomers</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Net optical rotation is zero.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Process of conversion of enantiomer into racemic mixture is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Racemization</option><option id="B">Resolution</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Loss of optical activity.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which mechanism (SN1 or SN2) leads to racemization for chiral starting materials?</text>
            <option id="A">SN1</option><option id="B">SN2</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Planar carbocation can be attacked from either side.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reactivity of RX towards SN2 depends on ____ steric hindrance.</text>
            <option id="A">Electronic and steric</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Transition state is crowded.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Nucleophilic substitution: Aryl halides are more reactive when ____ groups are at o/p positions.</text>
            <option id="A">Electron Withdrawing (like -NO2)</option><option id="B">Electron Donating</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Stabilizes the intermediate carbanion.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Dow's process: Phenol from Chlorobenzene requires ____.</text>
            <option id="A">623 K, 300 atm, NaOH</option><option id="B">Room temp, NaHCO3</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Extreme conditions for nucleophilic substitution of ArX.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Allylic halides: Halogen is attached to sp3 C next to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Carbon-carbon double bond</option><option id="B">Benzene ring</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: CH2=CH-CH2Cl.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Vinylic halides: Halogen is attached to ____ carbon.</text>
            <option id="A">sp2 hybridized</option><option id="B">sp3 hybridized</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: CH2=CHCl.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Gem-dihalides have two halogens on ____ carbon atom.</text>
            <option id="A">The same</option><option id="B">Adjacent</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Ethylidene chloride.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Vic-dihalides have two halogens on ____ carbon atoms.</text>
            <option id="A">Adjacent</option><option id="B">The same</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Ethylene dichloride.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reaction of methane with excess chlorine in presence of light finally gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Carbon tetrachloride (CCl4)</option><option id="B">Methyl chloride</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Complete substitution by free radical mechanism.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Lucas reagent is a mixture of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Conc. HCl and Anhydrous ZnCl2</option><option id="B">NaN3 + HCl</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Used to distinguish 1°, 2°, 3° alcohols.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Highest rate of SN2 is for ____ halogen atom (among F, Cl, Br, I).</text>
            <option id="A">Iodide (I)</option><option id="B">Fluoride (F)</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>I- is a better leaving group.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Grignard reagents should be prepared under ____ conditions.</text>
            <option id="A">Anhydrous (dry ether)</option><option id="B">Aqueous</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Water reacts to form alkanes.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The major product in nitration of chlorobenzene is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">p-Nitrochlorobenzene</option><option id="B">o-Nitrochlorobenzene</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to symmetry and less sterics.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reaction of CH3Br + NaCN (aqueous ethanol) gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">CH3CN (Acetonitrile)</option><option id="B">CH3NC</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Ionic cyanide attacks through C.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Hydrolysis of acetonitrile (CH3CN) with acid gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ethanoic acid (CH3COOH)</option><option id="B">Methanoic acid</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Complete hydrolysis of nitrile to acid.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reduction of alkyl cyanides with Sodium/Ethanol is ____ reaction.</text>
            <option id="A">Mendius</option><option id="B">Stephen's</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Gives primary amines.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Haloalkanes having ____ have higher BP than alkanes of same molecular mass.</text>
            <option id="A">Greater polarity</option><option id="B">Multiple bonds</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Stronger intermolecular forces.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Iodoform test is given by compounds with ____ group.</text>
            <option id="A">CH3-CO- or CH3-CH(OH)-</option><option id="B">-COOH</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Yellow precipitate of CHI3 is formed.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which element is used to detect halogens in Lassaigne's filtrate?</text>
            <option id="A">Silver (Ag in AgNO3)</option><option id="B">Iron</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Formation of AgX precipitates.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>AgCl dissolves in NH4OH due to formation of ____ complex.</text>
            <option id="A">[Ag(NH3)2]Cl</option><option id="B">[AgCl2]-</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Soluble diammine silver(I) chloride.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>AgBr is ____ soluble in ammonia than AgCl.</text>
            <option id="A">Less (Sparingly)</option><option id="B">More</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Pale yellow color.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>AgI is ____ in ammonia.</text>
            <option id="A">Insoluble</option><option id="B">Highly soluble</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Yellow color.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reaction of RX with Mg in dry ether gives intermediate for synthesizing ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Alcohols, Acids, Hydrocarbons etc.</option><option id="B">Only Alkanes</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Versatility of Grignard reagent.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Chlorination of toluene in presence of light gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Benzyl chloride (Side chain)</option><option id="B">o/p-Chlorotoluene</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Free radical mechanism at methyl group.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Chlorination of toluene in dark with FeCl3 gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">o/p-Chlorotoluene (Ring substitution)</option><option id="B">Benzyl chloride</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Electrophilic substitution.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Carbon tetrachloride (CCl4) is used as ____ under trade name Pyrene.</text>
            <option id="A">Fire extinguisher</option><option id="B">Fuel</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Bismuth chloride (non-flammable).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Primary source of environmental concern with CFCs is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ozone depletion</option><option id="B">Acid rain</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Damages the protective layer.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reaction R-X + R'-O-Na+ -&gt; R-O-R' + NaX is ____ synthesis.</text>
            <option id="A">Williamson</option><option id="B">Wurtz</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Preparation of ethers.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Williamson synthesis works best with ____ alkyl halides.</text>
            <option id="A">Primary (1°)</option><option id="B">Tertiary (3°)</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>3° halides undergo elimination to form alkenes.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>SN2 reaction rate: RI &gt; RBr &gt; RCl &gt; RF. Correct? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Leaving group ability order.</explanation></question>
    </medium>
    <hard>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following is most reactive towards SN1?</text>
            <option id="A">Benzyl chloride [C6H5CH2Cl]</option><option id="B">Chlorobenzene</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Benzyl carbocation is resonance stabilized.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reactivity of ArX towards nucleophilic substitution increases with ____ at o/p.</text>
            <option id="A">Strong -M groups (e.g. -NO2)</option><option id="B">Strong +M groups</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Removes electron density from ring, facilitating attack.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Reaction of benzene with CH3Cl/AlCl3 gives toluene. This is ____ alkylation.</text>
            <option id="A">Friedel-Crafts</option><option id="B">Wurtz-Fittig</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Common electrophilic substitution.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following has the highest boiling point?</text>
            <option id="A">p-dichlorobenzene</option><option id="B">o-dichlorobenzene</option><option id="C">m-dichlorobenzene</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Wait, p-isomer has highest MP due to symmetry, but BP of isomers are often similar. p-isomer is most stable lattice.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which isomer of dichlorobenzene has the highest melting point?</text>
            <option id="A">para</option><option id="B">ortho</option><option id="C">meta</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Symmetry leads to better packing in crystal lattice.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Ambidentate nucleophile NO2- can bond via N to form Nitro and via O to form ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Nitrite</option><option id="B">Nitrate</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Linkage isomerism context.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Effect of solvent on SN1: Highly polar solvents ____ the reaction rate.</text>
            <option id="A">Increase</option><option id="B">Decrease</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Stabilizes the transition state and carbocation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Steric effect in SN2: Neopentyl chloride reacts ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Extremely slowly</option><option id="B">Very fast</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Despite being 1°, central C is heavily branched.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following cannot be used as a solvent for Grignard reagent preparation?</text>
            <option id="A">Ethanol</option><option id="B">Diethyl ether</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Protic solvents react with Grignard reagents.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Optical isomerism in haloalkanes was first explained by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Le Bel and van't Hoff</option><option id="B">Pasteur</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Based on tetrahedral carbon.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Specific rotation [α] depends on ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Temp, Wavelength, Solvent, Concentration</option><option id="B">Only Temp</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard polarimetry parameters.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Mechanism of reaction: ArX + NaNH2 / liq NH3 -&gt; ArNH2 + NaX is ____.</text>
